speech.p:
I beg to move,
That—


(1) public bills other than Government bills shall have precedence over Government business on 29th January, 12th Febuary, 26th February, 12th March, 26th March, 9th April, 7th May, 21st May, 18th June, and 2nd July;

(2) private members' notices of motions shall have precedence over Government business on 27th November, 4th December, 5th February, 19th February, 5th March, 19th March, 2nd April, 30th April, 14th May, and 28th May, and ballots for these notices shall be held after questions on 11th November, 18th November. 27th January, 3rd February, 17th February, 3rd March, 17th March, 14th April, 28th April, and 12th May, respectively;

(3) on Monday, 7th December, Tuesday, 27th April, Tuesday, 13th July, and Wednesday, 21st July, private members' notices of motions shall have precedence until seven o'clock. and ballots for these notices shall be held after questions on Monday 23rd November, Monday, 12th April, Monday, 28th June, and Tuesday, 6th July, respectively;

(4) no notices of motions shall be handed in for any of the days on which private members' notices have precedence under this order in anticipation of those ballots.

The proposals contained in the Motion are identical with those we have had in the House on Private Members' time for the last 12 or 13 years, with the addition of four half-days for Motions, introduced about five years ago, being also included in the Motion.

Most older hon. Members will know precisely how this works, but for the benefit of newer hon. Members I will mention the procedure. Twenty Fridays


are provided, ten for Private Members' Motions and ten for Private Members' Bills. Of the Private Members' Bills' days, the first six are devoted to Second Readings and the four last Fridays to subsequent stages, with Second Readings falling in at the end of the line, if there is time. The ten Fridays for Motions are balloted for approximately 16 days before the actual Motion takes place in the House, and for Private Members' Bills the general Ballot covering the whole of this Session takes place quickly after the beginning of the Session.

The dates, therefore, are that the Ballot for Private Members' Bills will be on 12th November. Bills will be presented on 2nd December, which gives hon. Members the opportunity of preparing their Bills in time. The first Ballot for Private Members' Motions will be on 11th November, with a debate on 27th November, exactly 16 days later. For the four half-days, again the Ballot will take place in the Chamber about 16 days before.

